  <article id="text__paragraphs">
   <header><h1>What is selector’s specificity and who it’s calculated?</h1></header>
   <p>
     Selector specificity is a value that determines which style rules are applied to an element when multiple conflicting rules exist. It is calculated based on the components of a selector. The specificity is usually represented as a four-part value: (a, b, c, d) where each part corresponds to the number of occurrences of different types of selectors in the CSS rule.
   </p>
  <header><h1>What are complex selectors?</h1></header>
   <p>
     Complex selectors are selectors that combine multiple simple selectors to target specific elements on a web page. These can include descendant selectors, child selectors, adjacent sibling selectors, general sibling selectors, attribute selectors, and more. By using complex selectors, you can target elements based on their relationship to other elements or based on specific attributes.
   </p>
  <header><h1>What is the difference between pseudo-classes and pseudo-elements?</h1></header>
   <p>
     Pseudo-classes are used to define a special state of an element. They start with a colon : followed by the pseudo-class name. For example, :hover, :active, :first-child. Pseudo-elements, on the other hand, allow you to style specific parts of an element. They start with a double colon :: followed by the pseudo-element name. For example, ::before, ::after, ::first-line.
   </p>
